'''James Colvin''' (1844 – 29 October 1919) was a New Zealand [[Member of parliament|Member of Parliament]] for {{NZ electorate link|Buller}}, in the [[South Island]].

==Early life==
Colvin was born in 1844 in [[Donegal]], Ireland, where he received his education.<ref name="Press obit">{{cite news|title=Mr J. Colvin, M.P., Killed|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=CHP19191030.2.43|accessdate=7 July 2015|work=[[The Press]] |volume=LV |issue=16667|date=30 October 1919|page=6}}</ref> He emigrated to [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria, Australia]] in 1861 and went [[Victorian gold rush|gold mining]] in [[Creswick, Victoria|Creswick]] and [[Daylesford, Victoria|Daylesford]].{{sfn|Scholefield|1940|p=171}} He came to New Zealand in 1862 and joined the [[Otago Gold Rush]] in [[Clyde, New Zealand|Dunstan]] and [[Wakatipu Basin|Wakatipu]], from where he went to the gold fields in the [[Wakamarina River|Wakamarina Valley]] in [[Marlborough Region|Marlborough]]; he set up a store in the latter place.{{sfn|Scholefield|1940|p=171}}{{sfn|Hamer |1988 |p=363}} When he was a young man, Colvin was held up by a member of the Burgess-Sullivan gang (also known as the [[Maungatapu murders|Maungatapu Murderers]]) near where George Dobson had been murdered a few days previously. Unknown to his interrogator James Colvin was carrying 2,000 pounds worth of gold on his saddle, and managed to pass unmolested.{{sfn|Matthews|1999|p=203}}

